Title:
DarkLoadLibrary

Type:
GitHub Tool

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- DarkLoadLibrary is a custom Windows DLL loader intended for offensive tradecraft, providing a “LoadLibrary-like” capability without relying on the standard loader path.  
- It supports loading a DLL either from disk (via a path usable by `CreateFileW`) or directly from an in-memory buffer, enabling fileless-style module loading.  
- An optional mode (`NO_LINK`) avoids linking the loaded module into the PEB module lists, reducing visibility to user-mode enumeration and some monitoring.  
- The project is associated with research on bypassing image-load kernel callbacks (commonly used by EDR for DLL load telemetry), indicating a focus on evasion of load-notification-based detections.  
- It is primarily useful for red teams, penetration testers, and implant/tooling developers who need controlled module mapping and execution behavior.  
- The author notes compatibility gaps versus the full Windows loader due to edge cases (imports, relocations, loader quirks), so some DLLs may not load correctly.

Technical Focus:
- Custom PE/DLL loading (manual mapping-style loader)
- Loading modules from memory buffers vs filesystem
- PEB module list linking/unlinking (stealth loading)
- Evasion of image-load monitoring / kernel callback telemetry
- Windows loader behavior and edge-case handling

Use Cases:
- In-memory loading of post-exploitation capability DLLs without dropping to disk
- Reducing module visibility by avoiding PEB linkage (`NO_LINK`)
- Testing/validating defensive detections around image-load events and module enumeration
- Building custom loaders for implants where standard `LoadLibrary` is too observable

